snippet.textDisplay:
Jazza - that was a trip a trip to watch bro, but if you ever work up the courage to take another run at this I have a hypothesis for you to test. The vulnerability of copic markers is that they aren't light fast. That is- they're intended to illustrate a piece for reproduction (print, photo, film, etc)- where the original will fade and wash out with time. Since they aren't light fast, we can assume that they're probably based off of a combination of dye and organic alcohol, rather than raw pigment and alcohol. Next time you're at your local grocer, take a look for some fabric dye- it's marketed as Rid dye in the states, but probably has a different brand in Australia. Typically near the detergent and bleach in the store. Then there's the issue of organic alcohol- most of the products made for human consumption are going to run 30-50% ABV: vodakas, whiskys, gins etc. What we would typically think of as "hard liquor" - but there exists a product that is the spawn of Satan and fuel for many a frat party punch spiking: Everclear. Pure grain alcohol usually has a picture of a corn cob on the bottle and is sold near where you'd get your bourbon. The stuff is glass-clear, 190-195 proof, incredibly polar, and combustible- in fact not so dissimilar to the ethanol you can burn in the gas tank of your car. So NO OPEN FLAMES if you pop the top on it. I bet if you mix grain alcohol with laundry dye, you'll get a liquid with a controllable saturation that drys quickly, flows and blends easily and with minimal damage to the paper- a sort of "ghetto copic."


...and then of course this opens the door to mix it with Kool-aid and make Grape Ape XD

*Cries in science degree*

This could be really interesting if done with scientific method: same amount of alcohol, same amount & colour pigment for each test. The final test should've been the brush pens with both vodka & copic mix (or better yet empty copics but that would be an expensive test) as testing against the marker is always going to be different/inferior, etc. I wonder if there must be more than just the copic liquid and raw pigment powder in the copic blend or if the process of soaking the marker core with it prevents separation.

The "drunk guy" is mentioned as an explaination of the whole Copic marker numbering system in the "Marker painting foundations workshop" that she lauched a couple of years ago. She pictured him as a drunk guy from Japan as the Too company is Japanese, but it could just as well be you it seems ;) I really don't know how you could get that messy with paint all over even before starting drinking the alcohol :D


I liked this video a lot, and hope you will do more like this in the future just because you can.
